text:
I wanted to take a crack at this. I downloaded MySQL and created a table of this data and came up with this;

with 
inbound_inv as (
	select a.ID, a.OnHandQuantityDelta, a.event_type, a.event_datetime , sum(OnHandQuantityDelta) over (order by a.event_datetime) as runningInBound
	from inv_log a
	where a.event_type = 'InBound'
	and date(a.event_datetime) <= @age_as_of
	group by a.ID, a.OnHandQuantityDelta, a.event_type, a.event_datetime
	order by a.event_datetime), 
outbound_sum as (
	select sum(b.OnHandQuantityDelta) as allOut from inv_log b
	where b.event_type = 'OutBound'
	and date(b.event_datetime) <= @age_as_of), 
aging_data as (
	select
	case when c.runningInBound - d.allOut > c.OnHandQuantityDelta 
		then c.OnHandQuantityDelta 
	else greatest(0,c.runningInBound - d.allOut)
	end as InboundLeft,
	case 
		when datediff(@age_as_of, c.event_datetime) between 0 and 90 then '0-90'
		when datediff(@age_as_of, c.event_datetime) between 91 and 180 then '91-180'
		when datediff(@age_as_of, c.event_datetime) between 181 and 270 then '181-270'
		when datediff(@age_as_of, c.event_datetime) between 271 and 365  then '271-365'
		else '365 +' 
	end as agingCategory
	from inbound_inv c, outbound_sum d)
select ifnull((select sum(InBoundLeft) from aging_data where agingCategory = '0-90'),0) as '0-90 days old',
       ifnull((select sum(InBoundLeft) from aging_data where agingCategory = '91-180'),0) as '91-180 days old',
       ifnull((select sum(InBoundLeft) from aging_data where agingCategory = '181-270'),0) as '181-270 days old',
       ifnull((select sum(InBoundLeft) from aging_data where agingCategory = '271-365'),0) as '271-365 days old',
       ifnull((select sum(InBoundLeft) from aging_data where agingCategory = '365 +'),0) as '365+ days old';

text:
Here is my MSSQL solution
with cte_current as (
select top 1 OnHandQuantity AS CurrentQuantity
	,event_datetime AS CurrentDate
from warehouse
order by event_datetime desc
)
, cte_data as (
select *
	,sum(OnHandQuantityDelta) over (order by event_datetime desc) AS CumulatedQuantity
	,DATEDIFF(DAY,event_datetime,CurrentDate) AS Age
	,CASE 
		WHEN DATEDIFF(DAY,event_datetime,CurrentDate) <=  90 THEN '0-90'
		WHEN DATEDIFF(DAY,event_datetime,CurrentDate) <= 180 THEN '91-180'
		WHEN DATEDIFF(DAY,event_datetime,CurrentDate) <= 270 THEN '181-270'
		WHEN DATEDIFF(DAY,event_datetime,CurrentDate) <= 365 THEN '271-365'
	END AS AgeGrouping
from warehouse w
	cross join cte_current
where event_type = 'InBound'
)
SELECT 
	 ISNULL([0-90]	 ,0) AS [0-90]
	,ISNULL([91-180] ,0) AS [91-180]
	,ISNULL([181-270],0) AS [181-270]
	,ISNULL([271-365],0) AS [271-365]
FROM   
(select AgeGrouping
	,sum(iif(CurrentQuantity-CumulatedQuantity>0,OnHandQuantityDelta,OnHandQuantityDelta+CurrentQuantity-CumulatedQuantity)) AS Quantity
from cte_data
group by AgeGrouping
having sum(iif(CurrentQuantity-CumulatedQuantity>0,OnHandQuantityDelta,OnHandQuantityDelta+CurrentQuantity-CumulatedQuantity)) > 0) p  
PIVOT  
(  
SUM (Quantity)  
FOR AgeGrouping IN  
( [0-90], [91-180], [181-270], [271-365] )  
) AS pvt

text:
(at 5 minutes in) I actually work with SQL in a warehouse, and I would stop here and say the question and scenario is flawed. The warehouse management system should be redesigned first as it will have major issues in real warehousing scenarios.

The assumption that a warehouse that is designed to use FIFO will actually always do so assumes that no mistakes ever happen, no inventory ever gets misplaced, and nothing is ever manually moved outside the system design specifications. Among other things, a warehouse management system should know the current location, receipt date (or expiration date), and quantity for each pallet/location individually.

When you're already storing this information, the original question becomes trivial.

Also, the question does not account for inventory over a year old. Rare though it may be, it might still happen.
A report I use regularly identifies product over 2 years old, since at that point we have to start worrying about age-related effects.

text:
I took an entirely different approach:

I chose to just bucket everything and then tally through the buckets and then pivot everything. (I would have used the greatest function instead of a case statement but... Sequel refused to process it (I know oracle and DB2 support this [In fact in DB2 I can use max to process a list instead of as an aggregate function... I miss working with DB2])

with last as (
select max(event_datetime) bkt from warehouse),
buck as (
select DATEADD(day,-90, bkt) bkt1, DATEADD(day,-180, bkt) bkt2, DATEADD(day,-270, bkt) bkt3,
DATEADD(day,-360, bkt) bkt4 from last),
bucks as (
select a., (case when event_datetime >= bkt1 then 1
when event_datetime >= bkt2 then 2
when event_datetime >= bkt3 then 3
else 4 end) bucket
from warehouse a cross join buck),
tally as (
select sum(case when event_type='InBound' then OnHandQuantityDelta else 0 end) inp,
sum(case when event_type='OutBound' then OnHandQuantityDelta else 0 end) out,
a.bucket
from bucks a
group by a.bucket),
summs as (
select coalesce(inp,0) inp, coalesce((select sum(b.inp) from tally b where b.bucket>a.bucket),0) -
(select sum(b.out) from tally b) out, c
from tally a right outer join (select from (values(1),(2),(3),(4)) as x(c)) b on bucket=c)
/* I get to use a right outer join, joy */
select * from (
select (case when inp+out<0 then 0 when out<0 then inp+out else inp end) inp, c
from summs) t
pivot(
sum(inp)
for c in ([1], [2], [3], [4])) as p
author: Rick

text:
Interesting question, I haven't written any SQL for a few years and thought I'd have a go.

This is the logic that I came up with, reading the comments, others have suggested something similar:

Find the total quantity of all the outbound stock.
    This can be found using a windowing/analytic function rather than a separate query.

For the inbound stock group into a number of buckets 90 days wide. 
    This avoids having to repeat code.
    The bucket number is simply the latest event date minus the event date all divided by 90.
        The latest event date can be found using a windowing/analytic function rather than a separate query.

Now, starting from the last bucket, subtract the total outbound stock until it has all been accounted for.

At this stage the results are in a column where they can easily be pivoted into the required row.


Happy to share the code if you're interested.

author: Ritesh Sharma

text:
One Comment I have about your Query for the sake of consistency and loading time.

Replace your initial  *  with the deliberate list of the columns.

Explanation: This is because of Expansion, Redundancy and Query Optimisation, 

Expansion: Sometimes a 4 column datawarehouse may become 15 - 40 columns wide.

Redundancy: When you execute with * you get all the columns, even if you actually don't use them, and as the datawarehouse ages the query will be pulling redundant data increasing I/O for that query (Wear on the Hardware)

Query Optimisation:  The server engine will scope CPU for the full table in the first instance before your filtering, so to improve performance, moving forward always deliberately select what you need not everything from the table. This will also Index much faster because Deliberate Scope within the Statistics is easier for a CPU to handle as  the CPU does not have to check the columns it needs to pul because they are all declared. Note: The query optimiser will probably do the same.

text:
To add a little bit, there is a function called ISNULL(). This function takes two values. The function evaluates the first value. If the first value is NULL, it will return the second value, regardless of its value. 

So, ISNULL(NULL,'Hello') returns Hello. 

Coalesce uses this same exact logic but allows you to include multiple values, always in left to right order.

So, COALESCE(NULL,'HI','BYE') returns Hi. It never gets to evaluate BYE, as it falls to the right of a valid return value. If all of the COALESCE values are NULL, it will return NULL. 

Just to add flexibility, 6ou can use a CASE statement to do the same thing as ISNULL OR COALESCE. 

For ISNULL:
CASE
       WHEN MyValue is NULL THEN  MySecondValue
       ELSE MyValue 
END 

For COALESCE:
CASE
       WHEN MyValue is NULL THEN CASE
                                                                          WHEN MySecondValue is NULL THEN MyThirdValue
                                                                          ELSE MySecondValue
                                                                END
         ELSE My first value
END

text:
What if we first prepare a dataset with all the remaining goods ages and aggregated stocks by age, and then from that small dataset you will be able to get an easy select of specific ages: 

select age, sum(remaining) as total_remaining from
(select floor(EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM ('2020-05-25 23:59'::timestamp - ins.event_datetime))/(90*24*60*60)) as age, least(ins.onhandquantitydelta, ins.onhandquantity - sum(outs.onhandquantitydelta)) as remaining
from schemaname.wh as ins cross join schemaname.wh as outs
where ins.event_type = 'inbound' and outs.event_type = 'outbound' and
outs.event_datetime > ins.event_datetime
group by ins.id) as balance
where balance.remaining>0
group by age;

in my query result age=0 is 0-90 days, age=1 is 91-180, etc
age   | total_remainig
0	  |  176
1	  |  102

text:
I would have put the ranges (0,90 & description..etc.)  into a cte table then left join it in a subsequent cte to categorise the dataset rows. 
Then use dynamic sql to pivot on the category column. In the future you can then add a new category and range to the first cte and the subsequent queries would remain unchanged.
Also case statements run on each row so as your dataset grows the query scalling is affected. A table of category values left joined should scale better but that's not tested

author: Leighton

text:
First, this is a very good explanation so I don't want to detract from that.  However, in watching, I had to say that you jumped through a lot of hoops in the effort to keep this the way it is.  As some previous commenters pointed out, you could use various partition and window functions within the query to make things a bit easier.  Personally, I tend to avoid that approach.  I don't tend to care too much for nuanced and very complex queries that could get run on large tables - especially if there might be multiple people working with the report or code eventually.  The one thing I've learned is that the phrase "competent with SQL" is a very, very inclusive grouping.

Ideally, I would incorporate the bulk of my logic into a function.  Using something like pl/sql or pl/pgsql would allow you the internal freedom to have flow control and other elements.  But, more to the point, if you have a defined table structure, you can create a generic function to return in integer representing ending inventory for an arbitrary period.  Say it was named "ending_inventory" and took two integers for starting days from today and ending days from today as an argument.  Then your final query would be as simple as ""SELECT ending_inventory(0, 90) as '0-90 days',¬†ending_inventory(91, 180) as 91-180 days', ... etc.

This could easily be continued as far back as you wanted or could easily be wrapped into a programmatic loop to be built dynamically by a reporting engine.  As a function, it also allows the underlying code to be maintained without much disturbance of the front end and can be tuned much easier or, in the event of performance issues, promoted to a different language or function type.  I personally like to think down the road when this report has been around the block for five years, the original author is long gone, the table has grown to millions of entries, and something weird breaks.  What's the easiest path to resolution?

author: techTFQ

text:
¬†@techTFQ¬† What you are missing is that you set event_datetime as your first day instead of using  
CURRENT_TIMESTAMP() (or equivalent in your database of choice).  What you are doing is you are getting the earliest datetime from the table.  No where in the problem did it say that the first entry is the first day.  That is your assumption and it is a wrong assumption.  This has nothing to do with the data in the table.  If you run your query today vs 200 days later, you will get the same results.  Unfortunately, that isn't what the question asked.  If you were asked what the inventory age in relation to the last inbound/outbound receieved, then your code will work.
author: Leighton

text:
Hi Rei,

Was it mentioned in the question that you need to find the age of inventory as of current day ?

If they specified explicitly that we needed to find the age as per current day then yes, using the current date from database would make sense but in this question they just asked for the age as per the given data ..

I fact the last shipment is on May 2020 and if I assumed current day as Day 1 then the output would be not as expected by this question..

As per their given output they kind of wanted us to treat last event date time as the Day 1 from when we needed to calculate the age..

This question was asked to my subscriber just last month so it‚Äôs not like this question was asked during May 2020..

I hope this clears your confusion..
author: techTFQ

text:
¬†@techTFQ¬† We can agree to disagree but the question was to generate an sql that will create a report for how long the inventory has been in the warehouse.  It does not have to give you every detail.  As part of the interview process, it is your job to ask questions.  Since you weren't doing the interview and couldn't ask questions I can understand your logic.  Also, the sample output is just that, a sample output.  That sample output was valid for some amount of days but isn't valid today if you run the script today. Unless specifically stated, sample outputs are not your goal.  As an engineer, you are expected to come up with your own set of tests and think about when/how your solution does and does not work.

I'm just saying if you were asked to generate an sql that would be used to generate reports, your sql will not generate the correct report the longer a shipment has not gone in or out of the warehouse.  If this is a busy warehouse then your solution is not a problem.
author: Leighton

text:
I understand your point of view but I am just saying for this question in the interview based on the expected output the last shipment date should have been the day 1(since the question was asked in Nov 2021 and the data was as per May 2020) 

If this was a real project then I would have done this using a procedure and a function and considering a lot more scenarios than what was given in the sample data here..

Anyways, you did make a good point and I appreciate your effort in explaining it..
üôèüèº
author: techTFQ

text:
‚Äã¬†@Leighton¬† First of all, I think you're way overthinking things. What you're harping on is as simple as replacing d.day90 with today's date and time function. I would hope that the question is trying to see and understand your logic in solving the problem and the query that you use to do so rather than a very simple gotcha in the form of "uh oh the data was from last year though so by you using the sample data as a reference for the expected output you've failed". 

Also honestly, It's assumptive either way. Maybe the report was needed to see how long inventory stayed in the warehouse back in May 2020? Maybe the next step is a comparison from then to now to see how efficient they've been with only ordering what they need each inbound shipment. The question isn't clear and it's actually incorrect for you to assume the report needs to be current info as well. If this was a job you'd ask who needed the data what the intended use was. In an interview you'd ask the interviewer and at that point it's up to them as to what the report is trying to accomplish. I'm not sure why you want to have this "Umm, actually..." attitude when the main point of a video like this would be to teach the logic behind the query and not literally build a report based on data that you can copy and paste to use for yourself.
